The CFA’s core holding is that **s 161(1)(c) of the Crimes Ordinance does not apply to the use of a person’s own computer, unless that use involves accessing another computer**. This conclusion rests on three interrelated analyses: text, context, and legislative purpose.  

#### a. Textual Construction: "Obtain Access" Implies Third-Party Computers  
The Court emphasized the ordinary meaning of "obtain access":  
- "Obtain" (defined as "acquire what one does not have") and "access" (admittance to use) inherently require gaining entry to something *not already in possession*. Using one’s own computer cannot qualify because the user already has lawful access.  
