The offense was created to address a gap in pre-1993 law: preparatory acts of accessing computers to plan fraud (e.g., stealing bank data) that were not criminalized until then. The Working Group’s recommendation explicitly referred to "gaining access to computers"—a phrase the Court interpreted as referring to *others’ computers*, not the user’s own. Legislative Council debates confirmed this: the statute was meant to penalize "access to a computer for acts preparatory but falling short of the commission of a fraud" (e.g., accessing a company’s computer to steal credit card details), not personal use.  

